  { question: "How long will it take to pay off my credit card?", answer: "The time to pay off your credit card depends on your balance, APR, and monthly payment. For example, a $5,000 balance at 20% APR with a $200 monthly payment takes about 32 months and costs roughly $1,360 in interest. Our calculator shows you the exact timeline and total cost based on your specific numbers." },
  { question: "How much interest will I pay on my credit card?", answer: "Total credit card interest depends on your balance, APR, and how quickly you pay it off. Credit card interest compounds monthly on the remaining balance. A $10,000 balance at 22% APR with $300 monthly payments results in approximately $3,400 in total interest over 45 months. Increasing your payment to $500 per month reduces total interest to about $1,700." },
  { question: "What happens if I only make minimum payments?", answer: "Making only minimum payments, typically 1-3% of the balance, means it can take decades to pay off your credit card. For a $5,000 balance at 20% APR, minimum payments of 2% ($100 initially, declining over time) could take over 30 years to pay off and cost more than $8,000 in interest alone, more than the original balance." },
  { question: "Should I pay off the card with the highest rate or lowest balance first?", answer: "The debt avalanche method (highest rate first) saves the most money in total interest. The debt snowball method (lowest balance first) provides quicker psychological wins. Mathematically, the avalanche method is superior, but many people find the snowball method more motivating, which helps them stick with the payoff plan." },
